Coupling: If theri are 2 components and both are depends on each other this dependency is known as coupling.
Eg-
class A{// this class is Component 1
    static int i = B.J;
}
class B extends A{// this class is Component 2
    static int J = C.m1();
}
class C extends B{// this class is Component 3
    public static void m1() {
        return D.K;
    }
}
class D extends C{// this class is Component 4
    static int k = 10;
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        D d = new D();
    }
}
Here i depends on J of B(B.J), we get J from return type of m1()(C.m1()), and return type of m1() is K of D (D.K)
So, here we have lot's of dependency A -> B -> C tightly coupled. Tightly coupling is not preferred, it will always be low.
Maintenance cost increased in case of tight coupling and reusability of code also decrease.

Cohesion: Due to high cohesion enhancement become easy, maintenance also easy.
(Low coupling & high cohesion) preferred.

















































